AE 1: First Data Viz

UN Votes Introduction

How do various countries vote in the United Nations General Assembly, how have their voting patterns evolved throughout time, and how similarly or differently do they view certain issues? Answering these questions (at a high level) is the focus of this analysis.

Packages

We will use the tidyverse, lubridate, and scales packages for data wrangling and visualization, and the DT package for interactive display of tabular output, and the unvotes package for the data.

library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(scales)
library(DT)
library(unvotes)

Data

The data weâre using originally come from the unvotes package. In the chunk below we modify the data by joining the various data frames provided in the package to help you get started with the analysis.

unvotes <- un_votes %>%
  mutate(country =
           case_when(
             country == "United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland" ~ "UK & NI",
             country == "United States of America"                             ~ "US",
             TRUE                                                              ~ country
           )) %>%
  inner_join(un_roll_calls, by = "rcid") %>%
  inner_join(un_roll_call_issues, by = "rcid")

UN voting patterns

Letâs create a data visualisation that displays how the voting record of the UK & NI changed over time on a variety of issues, and compares it to two other countries: US and Turkey.

unvotes %>%
  filter(country %in% c("UK & NI", "US", "Turkey")) %>%
  mutate(year = year(date)) %>%
  group_by(country, year, issue) %>%
  summarize(percent_yes = mean(vote == "yes")) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = year, y = percent_yes, color = country)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~issue) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent) +
  labs(
    title = "Percentage of 'Yes' votes in the UN General Assembly",
    subtitle = "1946 to 2015",
    y = "% Yes",
    x = "Year",
    color = "Country"
  )

We can easily change which countries are being plotted by changing which countries the code above filters for. Your task is to change the country name to those you are interested in.

Note that the country name should be spelled and capitalized exactly the same way as it appears in the data. See the Appendix for a list of the countries in the data.

AE 2: Bechdel Test

In this mini analysis we work with the data used in the FiveThirtyEight story titled âThe Dollar-And-Cents Case Against Hollywoodâs Exclusion of Womenâ.

Your task is to fill in the blanks denoted by ___.

Data and packages

We start with loading the packages weâll use.

library(fivethirtyeight)
library(tidyverse)

The dataset contains information on 1794 movies released between 1970 and 2013. However weâll focus our analysis on movies released between 1990 and 2013.

bechdel90_13 <- bechdel %>% 
  filter(between(year, 1990, 2013))

ANSWER: using nrow(bechdel90_13) to get the number of entries

There are 1615 such movies.

The financial variables weâll focus on are the following:

  • budget_2013: Budget in 2013 inflation adjusted dollars
  • domgross_2013: Domestic gross (US) in 2013 inflation adjusted dollars
  • intgross_2013: Total International (i.e., worldwide) gross in 2013 inflation adjusted dollars

And weâll also use the binary and clean_test variables for grouping.

Analysis

Letâs take a look at how median budget and gross vary by whether the movie passed the Bechdel test, which is stored in the binary variable.

bechdel90_13 %>%
  group_by(binary) %>%
  summarise(med_budget = median(budget_2013),
            med_domgross = median(domgross_2013, na.rm = TRUE),
            med_intgross = median(intgross_2013, na.rm = TRUE))

Next, letâs take a look at how median budget and gross vary by a more detailed indicator of the Bechdel test result. This information is stored in the clean_test variable, which takes on the following values:

  • ok = passes test

  • notalk = women donât talk to each other

In order to evaluate how return on investment varies among movies that pass and fail the Bechdel test, weâll first create a new variable called roi as the ratio of the gross to budget.

bechdel90_13 <- bechdel90_13 %>%
  mutate(roi = (intgross_2013 + domgross_2013) / budget_2013)

Letâs see which movies have the highest return on investment.

bechdel90_13 %>%

What are those movies with very high returns on investment?

bechdel90_13 %>%

ANSWER: Any small value that provides a better view is acceptable. I used 8. Filtering the data could have been done in a variety of different ways. I used filtering within the ggplot data argument (see below). The subtitle also needed to be updated to relevant text. Finally, I updated the coord_cartesian to the same value (8) for a better view but this part was not mandatory.

Zooming in on the movies with roi < 8 provides a better view of how the medians across the categories compare:

ggplot(data = bechdel90_13 %>% filter(roi < 8), mapping = aes(x = clean_test, y = roi, color = binary)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Return on investment vs. Bechdel test result",
       subtitle = "Zooming in at roi of < 8", # Something about zooming in to a certain level
       x = "Detailed Bechdel result",
       y = "Return on investment",
       color = "Binary Bechdel result") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 8))
